# Knowledge retrieval order

## Rule
Read in this exact order before answering any question about the code:
1. `efp-ai-knowledge-base/dictionaries/lookups.json` — resolve acronyms, aliases, domain terms.
2. `efp-ai-knowledge-base/ai-brain/` — service cards, cross-service map, ownership matrix, gaps-and-risks, decision log.
3. `efp-ai-knowledge-base/01-EFP/` — overview, system map, glossary, routing guide, building blocks, workflows, database model, system architecture.
4. `<repo>/.cursor/agent.md` → `<repo>/.cursor/architecture.md` → `<repo>/.cursor/service-knowledge-base/*.md`.
5. Repo source code only when the `.cursor/` layer is silent.

## Why
Every `<repo>/.cursor/agent.md` opens with the same checklist: consult the knowledge base first. `ai-agent-routing-guide.md` encodes the mandatory step ordering. Skipping it produces confident-sounding but fabricated answers — exactly what `no-invented-facts.md` forbids.

## Constraints
- Never start from the source tree when the question matches a domain concept; resolve the concept via `lookups.json` + service cards first.
- When the ai-brain contradicts the source code, trust the source code and flag the ai-brain file for refresh in `/gap-report`.
- Record any file you had to open below the `.cursor/` layer as a gap (the `.cursor/` layer should have covered it).

## Examples

### Good
> Task: "Add a field to FRLC." Read order: lookups.json (FRLC = Freight Rate Level Charges) → `ai-brain/service-cards/fb-rates-go.md` (owner) → `fb-rates-go/.cursor/service-knowledge-base/core-components.md` → source.

### Bad
> Grepping the entire workspace for "FRLC" without resolving it via `lookups.json`, then guessing from match density.

